My time at VKAPS was really valuable - it was my first real exposure to working in a
professional flutter team, collaborating cross functionality and getting comfortable with
debugging and performing work. My internship there was scheduled to run through January 2026,
 and it wrapped up naturally at that point.

While i was wrapping up at Vkaps, I started looking for the next opportunity. 
where i could build on what i'd learned - specifically, i wented more ownership of live,
production - faced application rather than contributing features within an existing team 
structure. Thats what drew me to Foduu Technologies.

At Foduu, I'm working directly on a grocery delivery app that's already live with real users —
so the stakes are different. It's not just "does this feature work in test environment" It's
"Is this app stable, fast, and reliable for people who are actually placing grocery orders right
now". I found that responsibility appealing because it push u to think more like an 
engineer then just a feature builder - you just caring allot more about the edge cases, API,
reliablity and how the small bug can actually cost/affect the real customer's experience.  

There are also a practical side to it - Foduu gave me the chance to work across a broader
range of things: maintaining a live app, but also contributing to newer builds like the POS
system and the e-commerce app, so I'm getting exposure to different types of Flutter
projects rather than just one.

So overall, it wasn't that VKAPS wasn't a good fit — it gave me a strong foundation — it was
more that Foduu offered the next step: real production ownership and a bit more variety in the
kind of apps I get to work on.
